{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607097"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15946"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15946"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71147"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8637"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8718"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20683"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71147"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spleen produces both red and white cells in the second trimester.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the spleen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mesoderm of dorsal mesogastrium","Lateral plate mesoderm","Ectoderm of dorsal mesogastrium","Endoderm of ventral mesogastrium","Neural crest cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spleen develops from \u003Cstrong\u003Emesoderm of dorsal mesogastrium\u003C/strong\u003E during week five of embryological development. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe spleen forms when mesenchymal cells within the dorsal mesogastrium begin to condense. Initially, multiple masses of splenic tissue develop separately and then typically fuse to form a single organ. When fusion is incomplete, accessory spleens may persist, occurring in approximately 10% of the population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is in contrast to incorrect options including \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoderm of ventral mesogastrium\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eectoderm of dorsal mesogastrium\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the embryological origin of the spleen is important for explaining anatomical variations and developmental anomalies that may be encountered clinically.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The spleen develops from mesoderm in the dorsal mesogastrium during week five of embryological development","The spleen originates as multiple masses of splenic tissue that normally fuse to form a single organ","Accessory spleens occur in 10% of people due to incomplete fusion of splenic masses"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15946"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56618"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T14:36:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T08:26:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8637"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71147"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":